Summary of project + methods

This study is examining the association between DNA methylation and childhood eczema (up to around 10 years). Studies used different definitions, and in this report we’re checking whether the “stricter” defintions, most of which require a doctor diagnosis, give similar EWAS results to the more lenient definitions that only include rash symptoms. We split the EWAS into “strict” definitions and “lenient” defintions and meta-analysed each set of EWAS. Then we compared the results (see below).

We only used EWAS of childhood AD for the comparison. As a reminder, here is the general definition of childhood AD - cases: AD by age 10, controls:no AD by age 10

The association of each outcome with DNA methylation was originally explored using logistic regression and 3 models with different covariates, for this analysis we are simply using the fully adjusted model, adjusting for the following covariates:

  • sex + batch + maternal_age + maternal_smoking + maternal_SES + gestational_age + cell_type (+ selection_factors) (+ ancestry)

Strict definition cohorts
INMA 304 (144, 160) 47.4 Childhood atopic dermatitis was assessed through questionnaire data at different follow ups: 6 months, 14 months and 7 years. In each follow up, doctor diagnosis of eczema was asked to the parents. Cases were children reporting doctor diagnosis of atopic eczema at any age, while controls were children never diagnosed of atopic eczema. Early onset atopic eczema was defined when children were diagnosed at 6 or 14 months of age
PREDO 792 (54, 738) 6.8 Physician diagnosed atopic dermatitis in the child was reported by the mother at the child mean age of 44.1 (SD 9.3) months. Child sex, maternal smoking during pregnancy (yes, yes, but quit in early pregnancy, no), maternal education (primary, secondary, lower tertiary, upper tertiary), gestational age were derived from the Birth Registry. We used first two MDS components based on the genome-wide genotyping with Illumina array to adjust for the ethicity.
GOYA 517 (93, 424) 18.0

Childhood AD = A doctor has at some point said that the child has eczema/allergic rash, and this rash has been active within the last twelve months OR The child has had an itchy rash within the last twelve months, and this rash has affected one of the following places: the folds of the elbows, behind the knees, in front of the ankles, under the buttocks, or around the neck, ears or eyes OR The child has had either doctor diagnosed AD or rash, but not active within the last 12 months.

Early AD = A doctor has diagnosed the child with eczema/allergic rash that occurred before 2 years of age

Persistant AD = A doctor has diagnosed the child with eczema/allergic rash before 2 years of age, and this rash has been active within the last twelve months

Particpants were aged 7 when questionnaires were conducted.

Lenient definition cohorts
ALSPAC 673 (343, 330) 51 Early onset Cases = rash count of 2 or more from ages 6 to 30 months Controls = rash count <2 & missing <2 timepoints Set to missing if rash count ==1 & missing 1 timepoint Childhood Cases = rash count of 2 or more OR doctor diagnosis of eczema OR report of eczema by age 10 yrs Controls = rash count <2 & missing <5 timepoints Late onset (used to derive persistent eczema) Cases = rash count of 1 or more between ages 81 to 128 months OR eczema reported from 81 to 128 months Controls = no rash reported at all timepoints from 81 to 128 months & no eczema reported from 81 to 28 months Persistent Persistent rash or eczema = case for both early onset AD and late onset rash/eczema Persistent rash or eczema controls = control for both early and late onset rash/eczema Cases = have persistent rash and eczema Controls = do not have persistent rash or eczema Set to missing if persistent eczema but no persistent rash
CHS 197 (50, 147) 25 Eczema questionnaire data was collected at two time points for each participant in the analytic sample. Participants’ parents responded to “has your child ever had eczema?” at baseline and four years follow-up. Participants were six to seven years old at baseline, and nine to ten years old at follow-up. Early-onset eczema are those who responded “yes” to the questionnaire at baseline. Childhood eczema is defined those who responded “yes” to the questionnaire at baseline or follow-up. Persistent eczema is defined as those who responded “yes” to both questionnaires.
EDEN 153 (69, 84) 45 The children’s families were asked to fill in a detailed questionnaire on their child’s health and characteristics at 1, 2, 3 4, and 5 and 8 years. At each follow-up, eczema was defined as parental-reported skin itchy eruptions and rush in the previous 12 months that were coming and going intermittently and were affecting one of the following places: the folds of the elbows, behind the knees, in front of the ankles, under the bittocks, or around the neck, ears or eyes. A child was classified as: • case of childhood eczema if he had eczema at any of the time points, as compared to controls who never reported eczema by the age of 5yrs; (MODEL 1) • case of early-onset eczema if he had eczema before the age of 2 years, as compared to controls who did not report eczema by the age of 2; (MODEL 2) • case of persistent eczema if he had early-onset eczema and had persisting at the age of 5yrs, as compared to controls who never reported eczema by the age of 5yrs. (MODEL 3)
GenR 450 (69, 381) 15 Information about eczema in the past 6 months was collected at age 2 years (Has your child had eczema in the last 6 months? [Not as far as I know / Yes, did not go the doctor / Yes, went to the GP / Yes, went to the hospital]). Response rates for this questionnaire was 76%. Cases were defined as having eczema, independent of GP- or hospital attendance. At age 10 years, information on eczema in the past 12 months was assessed by a parental questionnaire (Age 10 years: In the past 12 months has your child had: any eczema? [Yes / No]. Data-collection at this age is currently ongoing in Generation R.
MoBa1 828 (398, 430) 48 Eczema/Atopic Dermatitis variables were calculated based on questionnaire data. - childhood_ae: case - atopic derm at 6mon, 18mon, 36mon, or 7y; control - no atopic derm at any of these time points - early_onset_ae: case - atopic derm at 6mon, 18mon, or 36mon; control - no atopic derm at any of these time points - persistent_ae: case - atopic derm at (6mon, 18mon, or 36mon) and curent 7y; control - no atopic derm at any of these time points
MoBa2 418 (179, 239) 43 AD definition for Early onset, by age 3, based on maternal report from the 6, 18 and 36 months of age. AD definition of persistent, no AD by age 7 based on maternal report.
VITO 78 (23, 55) 29 Information on eczema (atopic dermatitis) of the children was collected based on the ISAAC questionnaire (5). Children were considered as cases if parents reported a doctor diagnosis for eczema, or if rash symptoms were reported (i.e. parental report of itchy, scaly rash in the joints and creases of the body) at least at two timepoints during the 11 years of follow-up (mostly in combination with reported use of suitable medication). At this stage 7 children were excluded based on inconsistent reporting during follow-up, or when rash symptoms were reported at one time point only.
IOW-F2 605 (177, 428) 29 Eczema at infancy was determined using the International Study of Asthma and Allergies in Childhood (ISAAC) questionnaire completed by the mothers at three months, six months, and twelve months respectively. We defined eczema considering the criteria of chronicity and typical morphology of eczema, along with onset within 2 years (allowing for those who completed the questionnaire retrospectively). The questions used to define eczema are: • Has your child ever had a rash which was coming and going for at least 6 months? • Has your child ever had a rash or eczema that has lasted for at least 7 days or more? (do not count regular nappy rash). • Have any of these rashes at any time affected the fold of the elbows, behind the knees, in front of the ankles, on the cheeks or around the neck, ears or eyes? • Was this rash itchy? • At what age (months) did this rash begin?
• Has your child ever had eczema?
